      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v32-cohort",
      "strategy_id": "v32-cohort",
      "cohort_label": "v32",
      "hypothesis": "v32 cohort — Experiment A: 1s polling ALONE (no trailing TP). 5 mirrors of top base performers (velmono-dev, best-double, vel20-top5, bot-excl-climbing, vel2050-dd-base). Isolates the pure 1s polling effect from the trailing TP confound that hurt v26. Expectation: lower SL realized losses (close to configured -SL% instead of -SL%×1.4 with gap penalty), unchanged TP capture rate, marginal net SOL improvement. If v32 beats base by ≥0.3 SOL on matched n, 1s polling has standalone value worth rolling out broadly. If null effect, the 5s polling cadence is fine for SL/TP and we can save the RPC budget.",
      "prediction": {
        "target_net_sol": 4.5,
        "target_sol_per_mo": 12,
        "target_drop_top3": 1.0,
        "target_n": 250,
        "target_days": 14,
        "kill_criterion": "n>=150 and net_sol<0"
      },
      "status": "OPEN"
    },
    {
      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v33-cohort",
      "strategy_id": "v33-cohort",
      "cohort_label": "v33",
      "hypothesis": "v33 cohort — Experiment B: trailing TP with 5% drop (vs v26's 10%). 5 mirrors on the same universes. Hypothesis: the near-miss failure mode in v26 was driven by trailing TP exiting at peak-10% which lands below static TP. A tighter 5% drop captures the peak closer to its actual high, minimizing the near-miss loss while still allowing real moonshots to extend. Risk: tighter trail exits too early on real runners (gives up upside). vel20-top5 is the canary — already showed positive in v26 at 10% drop, see if 5% is even better.",
      "prediction": {
        "target_net_sol": 3.0,
